ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The periodicity of epidemics of mumps virus infection in Spain is an interesting phenomenon and may be a consequence of the properties of the vaccine strains incorporated into the MMR (measles, mumps, rubella) vaccines employed in earlier years. In a recent comparison (see: Demicheli V, Rivetti A, Debalini MG, Di Pietrantonj C: Vaccines for measles, mumps and rubella in children. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2012 Feb 15; 2:CD004407. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD004407.pub3; abstract available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22336803) the effectiveness of at least one dose of MMR in preventing clinical mumps in children is estimated to be between 69 percent and 81 percent for the vaccine prepared with Jeryl Lynn mumps strain and between 70 percent and 75 percent for the vaccine containing the Urabe strain. Vaccination with MMR containing the Urabe strain has demonstrated to be 73 percent effective in preventing secondary mumps cases. Effectiveness of Jeryl Lynn containing MMR in preventing laboratory-confirmed mumps cases in children and adolescents was estimated to be between 64 percent to 66 percent for one dose and 83 percent to 88 percent for 2 vaccine doses.

However there may be other reasons for the periodicity such as the proportion of the population receiving mumps virus vaccine.

Galicia is an autonomous community in northwest Spain, with the official status of a nationality. It comprises the provinces of A Coruna, Lugo, Ourense, and Pontevedra, being bordered by Portugal to the south, the Spanish autonomous communities of Castile and Leon and Asturias to the east, the Atlantic Ocean to the west, and the Bay of Biscay to the north. It had a population of 2 778 913 in 2012. Vigo is a is a city and municipality, the most populous city in Galicia, and the 14th in Spain.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Spain can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/5wxA. Maps of Galicia can be accessed at http:./www.map-of-spain.co.uk/galicia_maps.htm. - Mod.CP]
